.SH NAME
HTMLElement.load_event \- HTMLElement: load event
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]load\f[B]\f[R] event fires for elements containing a
resource when the resource has successfully loaded.
Currently, the list of supported HTML elements are: \f[CR]<body>\f[R],
\f[CR]<embed>\f[R], \f[CR]<iframe>\f[R], \f[CR]<img>\f[R],
\f[CR]<link>\f[R], \f[CR]<object>\f[R], \f[CR]<script>\f[R],
\f[CR]<style>\f[R], and \f[CR]<track>\f[R].
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] The \f[CR]load\f[R] event on \f[CR]HTMLBodyElement\f[R]
is actually an alias for the \f[CR]window.onload\f[R] event.
Therefore, the \f[CR]load\f[R] event will only fire on the
\f[CR]<body>\f[R] element once all of the document\[cq]s resources have
loaded or errored.
However, for the sake of clarity, it is recommended that the event
handler is attached to the \f[CR]window\f[R] object directly rather than
on \f[CR]HTMLBodyElement\f[R].
.RE
.PP
This event is not cancelable and does not bubble.
.SH SYNTAX
Use the event name in methods like \f[CR]addEventListener()\f[R], or set
an event handler property.
.IP
.EX
elt.addEventListener(\[dq]load\[dq], (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] { ... });
\f[I]// or\f[R]
elt.onload = (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] { ... };
.EE
.SH EVENT TYPE
A generic \f[CR]Event\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
This example prints to the screen whenever the \f[CR]<img>\f[R] element
successfully loads its resource.
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]img\f[R] id=\[dq]image\[dq] src=\[dq]favicon144.png\[dq] alt=\[dq]MDN logo\[dq] width=\[dq]72\[dq] />
<\f[B]div\f[R]><\f[B]button\f[R] onclick=\[dq]reload()\[dq]>Reload</\f[B]button\f[R]></\f[B]div\f[R]>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] image = document.getElementById(\[dq]image\[dq]);
image.onload = () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  document.body.appendChild(document.createElement(\[dq]div\[dq])).textContent =
    \[dq]loaded!\[dq];
};

\f[B]function\f[R] reload() {
  image.src = \[dq]favicon144.png\[dq];
}
.EE
